    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey so im doing a lot of hiit lately and my legs feel like they are burning like crazy during the sprints. can u explain what is actually happening with the lactic acid in my muscles when that happens? and how does my body get rid of it after i stop?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "During a high-intensity interval training (HIIT) session, your muscles are working harder than usual, and they need more energy than your body can supply through aerobic metabolism alone. So, your muscles switch to anaerobic metabolism, which doesn't require oxygen, and this is where the lactic acid comes in. It's a byproduct of this process, and it can make your muscles feel like they're on fire, especially during those intense sprints.\n\nAfter you stop your workout, your body starts to clear the lactic acid from your muscles. This process is known as lactate shuttle, where lactate is transported from the muscles to the liver, heart, and other tissues, where it's converted back into glucose or used in other metabolic processes. This helps to reduce the acidity in your muscles and prevent that burning sensation from becoming too intense. So, while it might feel like your legs are on fire during the sprints, your body is actually working hard to clear the lactic acid and keep you going. Just remember, though, that your body is always working to keep you in balance, even when it seems like you're being pushed to your limits. Keep up the good work, and soon enough, your muscles will thank you for the effort!",
      "source": "target",
